# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anycast
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anycast/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:anycast/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:anycast/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:anycast/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:anycast/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:anycast/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:anycast/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:anycast/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:anycast/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:anycast/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:anycast/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:anycast/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:anycast/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:anycast/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:anycast/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:anycast/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:anycast/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:anycast/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:anycast/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:anycast/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:anycast/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:anycast/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:anycast/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:anycast/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:anycast/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:anycast/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:anycast/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:anycast/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:anycast/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:anycast/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:anycast/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:anycast/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:anycast/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:anycast/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:anycast/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:anycast/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:anycast/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:anycast/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:anycast/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:anycast/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:anycast/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:anycast/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:anycast/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:anycast/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:anycast/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:anycast/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:anycast/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:anycast/multicast] In computer networking, **multicast** is a type of group communication where data transmission is addressed to a group of destination computers simultaneously.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicast can be one-to-many or many-to-many distribution.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicast differs from physical layer point-to-multipoint communication.
[src:anycast/multicast] Group communication may either be application layer multicast or network-assisted multicast, where the latter makes it possible for the source to efficiently send to the group in a single transmission.
[src:anycast/multicast] Copies are automatically created in other network elements, such as routers, switches and cellular network base stations, but only to network segments that currently contain members of the group.
[src:anycast/multicast] Network assisted multicast may be implemented at the data link layer using one-to-many addressing and switching such as Ethernet multicast addressing, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), point-to-multipoint virtual circuits (P2MP) or InfiniBand multicast.
[src:anycast/multicast] Network-assisted multicast may also be implemented at the Internet layer using IP multicast.
[src:anycast/multicast] In IP multicast, the implementation of the multicast concept occurs at the IP routing level, where routers create optimal distribution paths for datagrams sent to a multicast destination address.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicast is often employed in Internet Protocol (IP) applications of streaming media, such as IPTV and multipoint videoconferencing.
[src:anycast/multicast] Ethernet frames with a value of 1 in the least-significant bit of the first octet of the destination address are treated as multicast frames and are flooded to all points on the network.
[src:anycast/multicast] This mechanism constitutes multicast at the data link layer.
[src:anycast/multicast] This mechanism is used by IP multicast to achieve one-to-many transmission for IP on Ethernet networks.
[src:anycast/multicast] Modern Ethernet controllers filter received packets to reduce CPU load by looking up the hash of a multicast destination address in a table, initialized by software, which controls whether a multicast packet is dropped or fully received.
[src:anycast/multicast] Ethernet multicast is available on all Ethernet networks.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicasts span the broadcast domain of the network.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multiple Registration Protocol can be used to control Ethernet multicast delivery.
[src:anycast/multicast] IP multicast is a technique for one-to-many communication over an IP network.
[src:anycast/multicast] The destination nodes send Internet Group Management Protocol *membership report* and *leave group* messages, for example, in the case of IPTV when the user changes from one TV channel to another.
[src:anycast/multicast] IP multicast scales to a larger receiver population by not requiring prior knowledge of who or how many receivers there are.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicast uses network infrastructure efficiently by requiring the source to send a packet only once, even if it needs to be delivered to a large number of receivers.
[src:anycast/multicast] The nodes in the network take care of replicating the packet to reach multiple receivers only when necessary.
[src:anycast/multicast] The most common transport layer protocol to use multicast addressing is User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:anycast/multicast] By its nature, UDP is not *reliable*—messages may be lost or delivered out of order.
[src:anycast/multicast] IP multicast is always available within the local subnet.
[src:anycast/multicast] Achieving IP multicast service over a wider area requires multicast routing.
[src:anycast/multicast] Many networks, including the Internet, do not support multicast routing.
[src:anycast/multicast] Multicast routing functionality is available in enterprise-grade network equipment, but typically needs to be configured by a network administrator.
[src:anycast/multicast] The Internet Group Management Protocol is used to control IP multicast delivery.
[src:anycast/multicast] Application layer multicast overlay services are not based on IP multicast or data link layer multicast.
[src:anycast/multicast] Instead, they use multiple unicast transmissions to simulate a multicast.
[src:anycast/multicast] These services are designed for application-level group communication.
[src:anycast/multicast] Internet Relay Chat (IRC) implements a single spanning tree across its overlay network for all conference groups.
[src:anycast/multicast] The lesser-known PSYC technology uses custom multicast strategies per conference.
[src:anycast/multicast] Some peer-to-peer technologies employ the multicast concept known as peercasting when distributing content to multiple recipients.
[src:anycast/multicast] Explicit multi-unicast (Xcast) is another multicast strategy that includes addresses of all intended destinations within each packet.
[src:anycast/multicast] As such, given maximum transmission unit limitations, Xcast cannot be used for multicast groups with many destinations.
[src:anycast/multicast] The Xcast model generally assumes that stations participating in the communication are known ahead of time so that distribution trees can be generated and resources allocated by network elements in advance of actual data traffic.
[src:anycast/multicast] Wireless communications (with the exception of point-to-point radio links using directional antennas) are inherently broadcasting media.
[src:anycast/multicast] However, the communication service provided may be unicast, multicast, or broadcast, depending on if the data is addressed to an individual node, a specific group of nodes, or all nodes in the covered network, respectively.
[src:anycast/multicast] Wireless networks use electromagnetic waves to transmit data through the air, enabling devices to connect and communicate without physical cables.
[src:anycast/multicast] These networks come in various types, including Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, cellular, and satellite networks, each serving different purposes.
[src:anycast/multicast] In digital television, the concept of multicast service sometimes is used to refer to content protection by broadcast encryption, i.e. encrypted pay television content over a simplex broadcast channel only addressed to paying viewers.
[src:anycast/multicast] In this case, data is broadcast to all receivers but only addressed to a specific group.
[src:anycast/multicast] The concept of *interactive multicast*, for example using IP multicast, may be used over TV broadcast networks to improve efficiency, offer more TV programs, or reduce the required spectrum.
[src:anycast/multicast] Interactive multicast implies that TV programs are sent only over transmitters where there are viewers and that only the most popular programs are transmitted.
[src:anycast/multicast] It relies on an additional interaction channel (a back-channel or return channel), where user equipment may send join and leave messages when the user changes TV channel.
[src:anycast/multicast] Interactive multicast has been suggested as an efficient transmission scheme in DVB-H and DVB-T2 terrestrial digital television systems, A similar concept is *switched broadcast* over cable TV networks, where only the currently most popular content is delivered in the cable-TV network.
[src:anycast/multicast] Scalable video multicast in an application of interactive multicast, where a subset of the viewers receive additional data for high-resolution video.
[src:anycast/multicast] Another similar concept is Cell-TV, and implies TV distribution over 3G cellular networks using the network-assisted multicasting offered by the Multimedia Broadcast Multicast Service (MBMS) service, or over 4G/LTE cellular networks with the eMBMS (enhanced MBMS) service.
[src:anycast/unicast] In computer networking, **unicast** is a one-to-one transmission from one point in the network to another point; that is, one sender and one receiver, each identified by a network address.
[src:anycast/unicast] Unicast is in contrast to multicast and broadcast which are one-to-many transmissions.
[src:anycast/unicast] Internet Protocol unicast delivery methods such as Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and User Datagram Protocol (UDP) are typically used.
